<article>
    <h1>Bo&#xAD;som busi&#xAD;nesses</h1>
    <h2>Three women turn their per&#xAD;sonal en&#xAD;coun&#xAD;ters with breast cancer into busi&#xAD;nesses with a pur&#xAD;pose</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201016/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-16"><time>2020-10-16</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Amanda Chai aman&#xAD;dac@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>In Sin­ga­pore, breast cancer re­mains the most com­mon cancer among women.</p>
    <p>Be­tween 2013 and 2017, nearly six breast cancer cases were di­ag­nosed each day, ac­cord­ing to data from the Sin­ga­pore Cancer Reg­istry.</p>
    <p>One in 13 Sin­ga­porean women will de­velop breast cancer be­fore the age of 75, the data found.</p>
    <p>Yet breast cancer sur­vivors The Straits Times spoke to were in agree­ment on one thing: It is not the end of the world and early de­tec­tion makes all the dif­fer­ence in sav­ing lives.</p>
    <p>If de­tected at an early stage, breast cancer is very treat­able, says en­tre­pre­neur Char­lene Koh, 37, who was di­ag­nosed with stage 1 breast cancer last year.</p>
    <p>Be­cause the di­ag­no­sis of the disease is such a big shock, many women who bat­tle and sur­vive breast cancer look at and live life dif­fer­ently.</p>
    <p>With re­newed per­spec­tive on the world, some are chan­nelling their pur­pose and mes­sage into build­ing busi­nesses that can help other women.</p>
    <p>This Breast Cancer Aware­ness Month, ST speaks to three en­trepreneur­s who turned their cancer jour­neys into busi­nesses with a pur­pose.</p>

